@NODE Abstract "AGuide - What is it"

Abstract
--------

Commodore's  hypertext  system  AmigaGuide  is mainly a shared library
(amigaguide.library)  which  may either be called by an application to
provide  an online-help system or by a stand-alone tool to view .guide
files.  Commodore's  AmigaGuide  program  (not to be confused with the
AmigaGuide system at large!) is such a tool. AGuide is another.

The  main motivation to write AGuide was to fix these two flaws in the
AmigaGuide tool:
- no file requester support
- no means to open its own screen

Yeah,  I  know, both can be circumvented by some plumbing (wild script
file hacking), but that is ugly after all.

On  the  other  hand, in V1.0 of AGuide, not the full functionality of
the AmigaGuide rool has been reimplemented:
- no support for XREFs
- no equivalent for the DOCUMENT and LINE arguments

If you do not know these, you probably do not need them.
If you badly need them, ask @{"me" link Author}, and I will see what I will do for you.


    "Calm down, it's only 1s and 0s." - anon.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation "AGuide - How to put it onto your system"

Installation
------------

Presumably   you   already  have  an  up-and-running  installation  of
AmigaGuide.  All  you  need  to  do is copy the AGuide program to some
directory  into  your path. Be sure to set its P protection bit, as it
is residentable.

If you use the environment variable scheme to parameterize the
behaviour of AmigaGuide, you may do just the same with AGuide. Simply
name the directory in ENV: (and ENVARC:) AGuide instead of AmigaGuide.
(See the AmigaGuide documentation for more on this topic.)


    "It works better if you plug it in." - Sattinger's Law

@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage "AGuide - Command line and Workbench parameters"

Usage
-----

AGuide may be invoked from a shell or from the Workbench.

Command line format: DATABASE,PS=PUBSCREEN/K,OS=OWNSCREEN/K,PN=PORTNAME/K

Tool types: PUBSCREEN, OWNSCREEN, PORTNAME


DATABASE - The name of the file to view.

When given as a command line parameter, the .guide suffix is optional.
When  AGuide  is started from the Workbench, the last selected project
icon - if any - is taken as this argument.

If  the  DATABASE argument is not provided or the respective file does
not exist, an ASL file requester will prompt for it.


PUBSCREEN - The name of the public screen to open on.

If  OWNSCREEN  is  not  present,  the  named  public screen (or if not
available the Workbench screen) is used for the AmigaGuide window.

If  OWNSCREEN  is present, a public screen of the given name is opened
and is used for the AmigaGuide window.


OWNSCREEN - Display mode of a screen to open.

If  this  parameter  is  present,  a  screen of the display mode given
(either  in  numeric  or name form (as set via BindMonitor)) is opened
and  the AmigaGuide window is opened in it. If the given screenmode is
not  available, the Workbench screen is cloned (thus, using a nonsense
screenmode   like  DEFSCRMOD  effectively  is  the  "clone  Workbench"
feature.)

If  PUBSCREEN  is  also  given,  the  screen is assigned that name and
opened as a public screen.


PORTNAME - Name of ARexx port for AmigaGuide.

(see AmigaGuide documentation)


Examples:

    AGuide OWNSCREEN PAL:Hires-Interlaced PUBSCREEN AGuide

brings up a file requester and the displays the selected file on a PAL
Hires  Interlaced  screen  which  is  opened,  named AGuide, and taken
public.

    AGuide UUCP:man/elm PUBSCREEN AmigaELM.1

displays UUCP:man/elm.guide on the public screen AmigaELM.1


    "The computer does what you tell it to do,
     not what you want it to do." - Joachim Graf

@ENDNODE

